05777nam a22008415i 9781442697843DE-B159720200623100627.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200623t20202009onc    fo  d z      eng d  a97814426978437 a10.3138/97814426978432doi  a(DE-B1597)551101  a(OCoLC)1163877791  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  aonccCA-ON 4aPN1949.S7bR65 2009eb 7aHIS0060002bisacsh04a792.72221 aRoss, Becki, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aBurlesque West :bShowgirls, Sex, and Sin in Postwar Vancouver /cBecki Ross. 1aToronto : bUniversity of Toronto Press, c[2020] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (368 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tPreface: Beginnings, Backlash, and Brazenness -- t1. Uncloaking the Striptease Past -- t2. 'I Ain't Rebecca, and This Ain't Sunnybrook Farm': Men behind the Marquee -- t3. 'We Were Like Snowfl akes - No Two Were Alike:' Dancers and Their Gimmicks -- t4. 'Peelers Sell Beer, and the Money Was Huge': The Shifting Conditions of Selling Fantasy -- t5. 'Everyone Wanted to Date a Dancer, Nobody Wanted to Marry One': Occupational Hazards in the Industry -- t6. 'You Started to Feel Like a Dinosaur': Exiting and Aging in the Business -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tList of Interview Narrators -- tPhoto Credits -- tIndex 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAfter the Second World War, Vancouver emerged as a hotbed of striptease talent. In Burlesque West,the first critical history of this notorious striptease scene, Becki Ross delves into the erotic entertainment industry at the northern end of the dancers' west coast tour - the North-South route from Los Angeles to Vancouver that provided rotating work for dancers and variety for club clientele. Drawing on extensive archival materials and fifty first-person accounts of former dancers, strip-club owners, booking agents, choreographers, and musicians, Ross reveals stories that are deeply flavoured with an era before "striptease fell from grace because the world stopped dreaming," in the words of ex-dancer Lindalee Tracey. Though jobs in this particular industry are often perceived as having little in common with other sorts of work, retired dancers' accounts resonate surprisingly with those of contemporary service workers, including perceptions of unionization and workplace benefits and hazards. Ross also traces the sanitization and subsequent integration of striptease style and neo-burlesque trends into mass culture, examining continuity and change to ultimately demonstrate that Vancouver's glitzy nightclub scene, often condemned as a quasi-legal strain of urban blight, in fact greased the economic engine of the post-war city. Provocative and challenging, Burlesque West combines the economic, the social, the sexual, and the personal, and is sure to intellectually tantalize.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jun 2020) 0aBurlesque (Theater)xHistoryx20th centuryxBritish ColumbiaxVancouver. 0aBurlesque (Theater)zBritish ColumbiazVancouverxHistoryy20th century. 0aBurlesque (Théâtre)xHistoirexColombie-BritanniquexVancouver. 0aDanseuses de revuexHistoirexColombie-BritanniquexVancouver. 0aNightlifexHistoryx20th centuryxBritish ColumbiaxVancouver. 0aNightlifezBritish ColumbiazVancouverxHistoryy20th century. 0aSex-oriented businessesxHistoryx20th centuryxBritish ColumbiaxVancouver. 0aSex-oriented businesseszBritish ColumbiazVancouverxHistoryy20th century. 0aShowgirlsxHistoryx20th centuryxBritish ColumbiaxVancouver. 0aShowgirlszBritish ColumbiazVancouverxHistoryy20th century. 0aStripteasexHistoryx20th centuryxBritish ColumbiaxVancouver. 0aStripteasezBritish ColumbiazVan